that he who maintains an unjust cause, will be victorious with a great slaughter of innocent persons. For there is then no blame imputable to him who, in such a case, prefers the combat which gives him the best hope which is to be had. But this also is true, that some things which may be done without blame, cannot without blame be approved by others3 though they may be permitted that graver evils, which can- not otherwise be avoided, may be avoided: as in many cases, usury and prostitution are tolerated.

5 Therefore what we have said above, when we spoke of prevent- ing war3 that if two persons between whom lies the disputo concerning a kingdom, are ready to fight it out in a combat, the people may allow it to bc so decided, that the greater calamity which otherwise impends may be avoided3 may be said here also, when the question is about terminating the war.
